pattern_result.executive_summary: React's codebase faces critical bus factor risks with single-person ownership of compiler (60% by josephsavona) and core reconciliation modules (55-79% by sebastian@calyptus.eu). Review quality varies dramatically by module familiarity, and several security-focused contributors are underutilized despite architect-level expertise.

insights.title: Compiler is a one-person show
insights.description: Joseph Savona owns 60% of compiler/packages with bus factor 0.19. This is React's most critical single point of failure - if he leaves, the compiler evolution stops. His review pattern shows he rubber-stamps non-compiler PRs, suggesting limited bandwidth to train others.

insights.title: Sebastian Markbåge is the secret React CEO
insights.description: Sebastian owns 55% of react-reconciler, 77% of react-client, and 79% of react-server - essentially controlling React's core runtime. With bus factors of 0.09-0.14, these modules would be paralyzed without him. No other contributor has comparable cross-module expertise.

insights.title: Hidden security experts being underutilized
insights.description: unstubbable has only 3 commits but delivered 3 deep/complex security fixes including DoS prevention (PR#35632) and streaming hardening. They understand React Flight's security surface better than most core contributors but aren't being leveraged for security reviews.

insights.title: Ghost maintainers still own critical code
insights.description: bvaughn@fb.com owns 16% of react-devtools-shared and git@andrewclark.io owns 25% of react-reconciler, but neither appear in recent commits. Their knowledge is silently draining while the codebase evolves without them.

insights.title: Review quality drops outside comfort zones
insights.description: josephsavona gives architect-level reviews on compiler code but rubber-stamps everything else. hoxyq thoroughly reviews DevTools but gives one-word approvals elsewhere. This creates blind spots where critical bugs could slip through cross-module changes.

insights.title: Rising stars with cross-module expertise
insights.description: Ricky (rickhanlonii) has delivered multiple deep/complex changes across reconciler, server components, and testing infrastructure. lauren (poteto) bridges compiler, DevTools, and ESLint plugin. These are your future technical leaders who can break down silos.

insights.title: DevTools team operates in isolation
insights.description: sebastian.silbermann (157 commits), hoxyq (33), eps1lon, and Ruslan Lesiutin primarily review each other's DevTools code. No cross-pollination with core React team means DevTools could diverge from React's architecture direction.

insights.title: One-hit wonders solving critical problems
insights.description: azat-io (1 commit) added ESLint v10 compatibility. AntonChesnokov (1 commit) fixed a validation bug. These contributors solved specific problems then vanished - they could be recruited for similar targeted fixes.

recommendations: Mandate josephsavona to pair-program compiler changes with rickhanlonii or lauren for 2 hours/week
Create 'React Core Internals' working group with Sebastian M. teaching 2 others reconciler architecture
Assign unstubbable as security reviewer for all React Flight/streaming PRs
Schedule knowledge transfer sessions from ghost maintainers (bvaughn, git@andrewclark) if still available
Implement cross-team review requirements: DevTools changes need core team review and vice versa
